Vice President Kamala Harris delivered a speech at the South Court Auditorium in the Eisenhower Executive Office Building. She thanked various leaders, including Secretary of Transportation Pete Buttigieg and Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency Michael Regan, for their dedication to improving health and wellbeing. Harris shared a story about a town called Mira Loma, which had severe air pollution, and emphasized the need to address pollution from heavy-duty trucks and buses. She announced that the Department of Transportation will provide $1.5 billion in grants to help cities and towns electrify their fleet of public buses, build infrastructure, and train workers. Harris also announced $2.2 billion in funding from the American Rescue Plan to support transit agencies and a proposed rule to reduce emissions from new heavy-duty trucks and buses. Additionally, she mentioned $17 million in grants for electric school buses. Harris highlighted the importance of transitioning to a zero-emission fleet to protect the environment, improve public health, and grow the economy.